result.execSummary:
The defendant Dennis M Funmaker Jr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Fine and court costs are to be paid as follows:  $50 is due on or before 10-1-17 and then $50 is due by the 1st of every month thereafter until paid in full.  Failure to pay any part of the fine or court costs in full by the due date will result in 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.  Cash bond of $150 has been applied.
Court deems sentenced to time served.

Defendant appears in person without counsel.  DA Kenneth Hamm appears specially for the State.  Defendant filed a waiver of counsel and plea questionnaire with the Court.  Charge and potential penalties were reviewed and he understands.  He states he will plead no contest.  Court performed elements/plea/waiver of rights colloquy with the defendant.  Defendant agrees with allegations in the complaint.  Court finds the defendant FVKI waives his right to an attorney, understands the proceedings, enters his plea and waives his rights.  

Court finds a factual basis exists and finds him guilty.  State recommends 20 days jail plus court costs.  State stipulates to 12 days jail credit.  State requests to apply cash bond on file to court costs.  Defendant agrees with the 12 days credit.  Court orders time served with credit for 12 days; $150 fine plus court costs ($642) including DNA surcharge.  Must submit a DNA sample.  Pay fine at $50 per month starting 11-1-17 with $150 cash bond on file applied.  FTP will be 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.
Spoke with defendant; he may be a few minutes late.
